name: texts/PROD_A.md
content:
# The production of medical research during the Covid-19 pandemic by document type group

## Covid-19 unrelated research

The panel and the table show the monthly output of medical research publications since January 2020. If only Covid-19 unrelated research is selected, the grey bars show how around <2% of the overall dataset are published each month. But the monthly share is lower in the beginning of the pandemic, e.g. with 1.79% in January 2020 (overall minimum) which indicates how the pandemic cut into the regular stream of publishing. 

The colored lines represent the share of the different genres and reveal the known pattern with a majority of common journal *Articles*, >10% of *Syntheses* such as narrative or systematic reviews, and even less for editorial material or preprints. There are almost no dynamics among the genres besides the rise in preprints in month 33 (September 2022) due to the indexing of additional preprint servers by OpenAlex.

name: texts/PROD_B.md
content:
## Covid-19 related research

In contrast, Covid-19 related research offers a very different picture. The dynamics in the production of items shows how only a negligible amount of items in the set was produced in the first three months, e.g. 80 items in January (0.02%) and 279 in February 2020 (0.07%). But the production rose sharply from March to June, where it lead to the third most productive month of Covid-19 related research. The monthly rate rises until its maximum in month 20 (2.91%) and then steadily decreases to rates below 2% since month 41 (May 2023). All in all, the production of Covid-19 related research starts with a stark hype in its first year and then gradually decreases with progress of the pandemic. 

The production of different genres of Covid-19 related research offers substantial dynamics. While the rates have been completely stable for other research topic, the pandemic kicks off with high rats of *Preprints* (37%) and *Problems* (19%) in March 2020. In comparison, *Articles* (38%) and *Syntheses* (6%) make up substantially lower shares in that month. This shows how the initial reaction to the pandemic relied heavily on uncertain evidence. Notably, editorials, letters, or news which we grouped as *Problems* play a large role in the initial reaction the pandemic, although they received comparably less public attention than *Preprints*. 
The overall trend in the genre dynamics of Covid-19 related research points into the direction of Covid-19 unrelated one: Mostly articles, a tenth of reviews and some shares for the rest. However, especially the 'rest' (*Preprints* & *Problems*) keep around twice the level compared to Covid-19 unrelated research. This indicates how many researchers may have made first experiences with preprinting during the pandemic, and kept this practice in the following. Even for unrelated research, the share of preprints increases slightly. Likewise, *Problems* may keep higher levels because they were not only used for a quick crisis response, but are also used to reflect on how science (and the journals) worked out pandemic publishing.
The rate of *Syntheses* culminates at 14% in month 11 (November 2020) from where it slowly but steadily decreases. The maximum might mark a consolidation point in the crisis response where already thousands of publications are published each month which have to be assessed and evaluated in order to define the scientific consensus on the different topics and guide decision making.

name: texts/RC_A.md
content:
# The Concentration of references
The data on this page tackles the question if there is a concentration of citations towards individual items. In general, citation distributions are heavily skewed that a small amount of items receives many citations while a majority receives only a few or none at all. The assumption is that this relationship may have been more severe during the beginning of the pandemic, for example that a handful of items have been highly influential. To reduce the number of dimensions and protect sanity, all genres of citing items were combined as it is the least interesting dimenion in this case.


## Herfindahl-Hirschman Index
The first two figures show the Herfindahl-Hirschman values for the different genres and corona status.
**Note/ToDo: Recalculate the HHI. I used an outdated formula for the HHI. It is based on the square of market shares, not absolute markets**

name: texts/RDT_A.md
content:
# References of corona-based research: type by type references

## Covid-19 unrelated research
The following figures reveal the references or evidence-based of research by document type genre and Covid-19 relatedness. If only Covid-19 unrelated (=false) *Articles* are selected, one can observe the straight lines in the lower pane. This shows that not only the production of the different genres is rather homogenous, but also their citations. But in contrast to the production, citations go almost completely to *Articles* (< 80%) and *Syntheses* (around 20%) with only fractions going to *Problems* and *Preprints*. It seems that it is highly uncommong to cite editorial discourse and not yet peer reviewed material. This only marginally changes for the other genres. 

In contrast, the upper window reveals some dynamics when Covid-19 unrelated items cited related ones. While the motivation remains unclear and might be also be partly due to missclassification in the data, it is noteworthy how especially *Problems* receive higher shares. This might indicate how publications about other topics refer to news or editorials when they refer to the Covid-19 pandemic in general. In addition, letters to the editor might have been used to criticise the methods and study designs of Covid-19 related research without discussing the content itself. *Note that the item-based calculations lead to erratic dynamics in the upper panel because the low number of overall items prohibits any smoothing effect.*

name: texts/RDT_B.md
content:
## Covid-19 unrelated research
If one switches to "Corona-relatedness = true", the picture changes dramatically. Corona-related research also cited unrelated ones. The lower rates of citations to *Syntheses* during the first five month indicate how Covid-19 unrelated research might have been cited for basic mechanisms or methods, but not for empirical results which are usually aggregated in systematic review articles. 

The upper graph now shows how Covid-19 related *Articles* (selection) cite other genres that are also about the pandemic. Similar to the production of items, there are visible yet more smooth dynamics during 2020. In sharp contrast, however, preprints are only marginally referenced with a maximum of 6% in March 2020 to a level that only once breaks 2.9% in Month 11 (November 2020). In contrast, *Problems* are the second most cited genre until Month 14 when they are overtaken by *Syntheses*. They reach their maximum in July 2020 (month 7) when they account for 19% of all references by Covid-19 related *Articles*! *Syntheses*, and *Problems* confirm this pattern so that one might ask whether the editorial discourse as part of the evidence-based of pandemic research has been highly neglected, especially in contrast to *Preprints*. 

But, if *Preprints* are selected as citing item, the dynamics are different. Here, preprints remain the second most important evidence-base until month 19 when they are overtaken by *Syntheses*. Therefore, especially *Preprints* seem to cite other *Preprints* while this effect disappears when they finally become journal publications. This might be because cited *Preprints* tend to be already published during the course of peer review. Or cited *Preprints* might get "weeded out" from the reference lists because they are seen as unreliable sources.

name: texts/RO_A.md
content:
# Overview over references of corona-related research
Publications have reference list to show on what previous works they are based. The type and amount of references a publication has tells us something about the evidence-based that is behind the claims of a research article. The next two figures provide an insight into two different dimensions.

The first figure just shows the average number of references per month, depending on whether the item is about Covid-19 (blue line) or not (green line). If *Articles* are chosen, one can see a small but constant increase, indicating that the number of references rises in general. In contrast, Covid-19-related articles had a much smaller but constantly rising reference count since the beginning of the pandemic. These dynamics are similar for the other items too. Notably, *Syntheses* revolve around 80 references per item which is the highest level.

name: texts/RO_B.md
content: The second figure shows what portion of references of any item was itself about Covid19-related research. In the case of *Articles*, references to Covid-related research made up half the reference list since April 2020 if the citing article is itself about Covid-19 (blue line). Not surprisingly, if the citing article is itself not about Covid-19, it only rarely referenced research that is. In contrast, over 72% of the references made by Covid-19 related *Preprints* are themselves about Covid-19 rekated content.

name: texts/intro.md
content:
# Analysis of Pandemic Document Types (PanDots)
**Alexander Schniedermann, Arno Simons**  
German Centre for Higher Education Research and Science Studies ([DZHW](https://www.dzhw.eu/) )  
Technische Universitt Berlin ([TU Berlin](https://www.tu.berlin/) )  
*Contact: schniedermann@dzhw.eu*

# Introduction

The Covid-19 pandemic required to quick addressation and reaction by scientific research, especially in biomedicine. As a result, usual behaviors and patterns in publishing changed substantially during the course of the pandemic. Most notably, medical research used preprinting in an unprecendented way [Fraser et al. 2021](https://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.3000959). Preprints are scientific articles that have been made public before any type of peer review has been performed. For this reason, they are often considered as preliminary, somwhat less robust, and their results should be taken with care [see Simons and Schniedermann 2023](https://www.degruyter.com/document/doi/10.1515/9783110776546-003/html?lang=de). In contrast, review articles and systematic reviews in particular aggregate previous research into a bigger picture. They are often used to combine results from multiple studies about with a similar research question in order to draw an overall or *final* result regarding that question. Therefore, results of reviews are considered as more robust and are usually placed first in the hierarchy of (medical) evidence [Schniedermann et al. 2022](https://www.taylorfrancis.com/chapters/oa-edit/10.4324/9781003188612-8/top-hierarchy-guidelines-shape-systematic-reviewing-biomedicine-alexander-schniedermann-clemens-bl%C3%BCmel-arno-simons). Besides epistemic characteristics such as preliminarity or robustness, document types may also represent particular scholarly functions. For example, comments on the current trends and problems in the field are published as letters to the editor by researchers, or as editorials by academic journals. Especially in medicine, important observations may also be published as case study before any systematic analysis is possible or feasable.

All in all, scholars have already argued how different stages of scientific discourses bear certain types of formal communication or publication genres [Cohen and Schnalle 1986](https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-94-009-4498-5).
While the bibliometric analysis of pandemic science has put much attention to preprints, no studies assessed thebroader contexts of publication genres during the Covid-19 pandemic so far. For this reason, this project combines the relevant data in an accessible and explorative way.

# Data
The basic underlying dataset are medical publications indexed in PubMed and assigned a PubMed identifier (PMID). In early 2024, the complete metadata record of PubMed as of December 2023 was retrieved. Since January of 2020, the first year of the pandemic, the set provides x unique PMID's. Since PubMed does not include preprint articles and only indexes citation links to other PubMed items, the database has been matched to OpenAlex in a second step. The OpenAlex snapshot of February 2024 as provided by the [German Competence Network Bibliometrics](https://www.bibliometrie.info) has been used for this purpose. After the matching, the dataset consists of x items.

**Preprints**  
Preprints are identified on the basis of registered source titles in OpenAlex. In contrast to the rest of the set, preprints do not necessarily have a PMID as they might not be registered in PubMed at all. In addition, preprints which are not from the medical domain are less comparable to the PubMed Set. For this reason, only those repositories were kept in the sample that have at least 15% of their preprints labeled as "Health Sciences" [topic in Open Alex](https://docs.openalex.org/api-entities/topics). Further details on the selection procedrue can be found in the openalex_exploration gitlab.
Therefore, the list of covered servers are: 
- 'bioRxiv (Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory)'
- 'Research Square (Research Square)'
- 'Europe PMC (PubMed Central)',
- 'Authorea (Authorea)'
- 'medRxiv (Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory)',
- 'Authorea'
- 'HAL (Le Centre pour la Communication Scientifique Directe)'
- 'Zenodo (CERN European Organization for Nuclear Research)'
- 'PsyArXiv (OSF Preprints)'
- 'OSF Preprints (OSF Preprints)'

**Identification of Corona-related Research**  
Whether a publication was about Covid-19 or not was identified in two steps. First, any publication that is assigned a Covid-19 related MeSH term was marked as Covid-19 related (see [NLM 2021](https://www.nlm.nih.gov/pubs/techbull/nd20/nd20_mesh_covid_terms.html) ). However, since there is some indexing time lag at NLM which also not indexes preprints at all, a title and abstract based system has been used in asecond step. Based on the Covid-19 related MeSH terms, titles and abstracts have been screened as well, using the following fulltext search in postgresql: `to_tsquery('english','coronavirus | (corona <-> virus) | covid | (sars <-> cov <-> 2) | sars-cov-2 | sars-cov2 | (sarscov <-> 2) | sarscov-2 | sarscov2 | ncov2019 | (ncov <-> 2019) | ncov-2019 | 2019ncov | (2019 <-> ncov)')`. Evaluating the second against the first approach, an overall precision of 0.9330 , recall of 0.9622 and F1-Score of 0.9474 have been retrieved. Therefore, the title and abstract based screening provided as solid classification approach.

# Methods
**Citation distributions**  
For the analysis of the dynamics in the citation distributions, Hogg's skewness and kurtosis for non-normally distributed data has been used [Bono et al. 2019](https://www.mdpi.com/2073-8994/12/1/19) . In addition, the Herfindahl Hirschman Index (HHI) was calculated for analyzing the citation concentration of the evidence-base of Covid-19 related research. To compare the HHI of different months, it is reported as monthly proportion of the maximum possible HHI of that month. The maximum HHI represents the hypothetical case in which a single article would receive all citations that were made that month. In contrast to other bibliometric analyses that use HHI, not the citation concetration of the cited articles was calculated. Rather, all citations that were made during a single month were conceived as the 'market', or evidence-base of research published that month [see Larivire et al. 2009](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/asi.21011) .

# Main Results
Among the many insights that can be obtained from the data, we identified three core takeaways...
